    "faq_zhAACx": {
      "type": "faq",
      "blocks": {
        "question_XamVPH": {
          "type": "question",
          "settings": {
            "title": "<strong>Causes</strong>",
            "text": "<p>There are several factors that can cause achilles tendonitis. The most common cause is over-pronation. Over-pronation occurs in the walking process, when the arch collapses upon weight bearing, adding stress on the achilles tendon.   Other factors that lead to achilles tendonitis are improper shoe selection, inadequate stretching prior to engaging in athletics, a short achilles tendon, direct trauma (injury) to the tendon, and heel bone deformity.</p>",
            "highlighted_text": "none",
            "highlighted_scribble": "circle"
          }
        },
        "question_x9EPUx": {
          "type": "question",
          "settings": {
            "title": "<strong>Treatment and Prevention</strong>",
            "text": "<p>Athletes, particularly runners, should incorporate a thorough stretching program to properly warm-up the muscles. They should decrease the distance of their walk or run, apply ice after the activity and avoid any uphill climbs. Athletes should use an orthotic device, heel cup, or heel cradle for extra support.   A heel cup or heel cradle elevates the heel to reduce stress and pressure on the achilles tendon. The device should be made with light-weight, shock absorbing materials. An orthotic device can be used to control over-pronation, support the longitudinal arch, and reduce stress on the achilles tendon.</p><p>If the problem persists, consult your foot doctor.</p>",
            "highlighted_text": "none",
            "highlighted_scribble": "circle"
          }
        }
      },
      "block_order": [
        "question_XamVPH",
        "question_x9EPUx"
      ],
